  "hash": "sha256:3a7f2c1d9e4b56a0f8c3d2e1b7a9f4c6d0e2b5a8f1c3d7e9b2a4f6c8d0e1b3a5",
  "signature": "ed25519:7b2a4f8c1d3e5a9b6c0d2e4f8a1b3c5d7e9f2a4b6c8d0e2f4a6b8c0d2e4f6a8b",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software quality assurance must satisfy Gradation 4: version-controlled source, automated regression test suite covering >90% of solver pathways, documented build and release procedures, and independent code review records. Required at MRL 5 for Class III device submissions.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9) is maintained under Git version control with tagged release branches. An automated regression suite of 312 test cases covers hemolysis transport, turbulence, and boundary condition modules. Build reproducibility is verified via containerised CI/CD pipeline. Independent code review was completed by a second engineering team with no involvement in model development. All artefacts are archived in the project document management system with FDA 21 CFR Part 11-compliant audit trails."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Numerical code verification must reach Gradation 4: method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to all governing equations including the hemolysis transport scalar, with demonstrated convergence orders matching theoretical rates to within 5%. Required because MRL 5 demands high confidence that solver implementation is free of systematic coding errors.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification was applied to the Navier-Stokes momentum equations and continuity, demonstrating second-order spatial convergence (observed order 1.94 vs. theoretical 2.0). However, MMS was not extended to the Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law transport scalar; instead, a simpler patch-test approach was used for that sub-model. This gap reduces the achieved level to Gradation 3. A corrective action item has been raised to complete MMS for the hemolysis scalar in the next solver release cycle, but the gap persists in the current submission."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Discretization error must be characterised at Gradation 4: formal grid convergence study using Richardson extrapolation on at least three systematically refined meshes, with Grid Convergence Index (GCI) reported for all QoIs. GCI for hemolysis index must be below 5% at the operating points of interest.",
      "rationale": "Three systematically refined hexahedral meshes (2.1 M, 8.4 M, and 33.6 M cells, refinement ratio 2) were generated using cfMesh. Richardson extrapolation was applied to the normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) and mean wall shear stress at all 5 operating points. GCI values for NIH ranged from 1.8% to 4.3%, all below the 5% acceptance threshold. Mesh topology was preserved across refinement levels to avoid introducing geometric discretization artefacts. Results are reported in Appendix C of the V&V report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must be characterised at Gradation 3: experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, outlet pressure, rotational speed) documented with measurement uncertainty, and deviations from nominal COU operating conditions quantified and shown to be within ±5% for all primary boundary parameters.",
      "rationale": "FDA inter-laboratory study experimental data provide inlet flow rates measured via Coriolis mass flowmeters (±0.5% full-scale uncertainty) and rotational speed via optical tachometer (±0.1 RPM). Outlet pressure was set via a downstream throttle valve with ±2 mmHg uncertainty. The five operating points span 2–8 L/min at 2500–3500 RPM, matching the COU envelope. Deviations between nominal and as-tested conditions were within ±2.1% for all parameters. Fluid temperature was maintained at 37±0.5°C using a recirculating bath, and blood analogue viscosity was verified pre- and post-test."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Output comparison must reach Gradation 4: quantitative comparison metric (e.g. validation metric E or ASME V&V 20 area metric) applied to all primary QoIs with uncertainty intervals from both simulation and experiment overlaid, and a formal validation decision criterion stated and evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 20 area metric for velocity profiles at three measurement planes (PIV data) and the absolute NIH at five operating points. Experimental uncertainty intervals were propagated from flowmeter, tachometer, and spectrophotometer calibration data. Simulation uncertainty intervals were derived from the Monte Carlo UQ study (1000 Latin hypercube samples over inlet turbulence intensity, fluid viscosity, and hemolysis model coefficients). The area metric for NIH ranged from 0.12 to 0.31 across operating points, indicating acceptable agreement. However, the formal validation decision criterion (threshold area metric value) was defined post-hoc after reviewing the results rather than a priori, which limits the achieved level to Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI relevance must be demonstrated at Gradation 3: the quantities measured in validation experiments are shown to be directly predictive of the clinical endpoint (hemolysis), with a documented traceability chain from experimental QoI to COU QoI.",
      "rationale": "The primary validation QoI is the normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) computed from plasma free haemoglobin concentration measurements, which is the same metric specified in the COU for regulatory submission. A traceability matrix (Appendix A) links each experimental measurement to the corresponding CFD output field. Secondary QoIs (velocity magnitude, turbulent kinetic energy) are validated against PIV measurements and are shown to be mechanistically upstream of the hemolysis prediction via the power-law damage accumulation model. The traceability chain is complete and documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity relevance must reach Gradation 4: validation experiments conducted on the same device geometry and at operating conditions fully overlapping the COU envelope, with documented justification that any remaining differences between validation and COU conditions are negligible or conservatively bounded.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is identical to the computational geometry. Operating conditions in the validation dataset span 2–8 L/min and 2500–3500 RPM, matching the COU envelope. However, the validation fluid was a glycerol-water blood analogue rather than human blood, introducing a potential discrepancy in viscoelastic properties and red blood cell fragility. A sensitivity study showed NIH predictions changed by less than 8% when viscosity was varied across the physiological range, but no formal bounding argument for the blood-analogue-to-blood extrapolation has been documented. This gap reduces the achieved level to Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error was assessed through iterative convergence monitoring and round-off error analysis. All simulations were run to residual convergence of 1×10⁻⁶ for all transported quantities. Double-precision arithmetic was used throughout to suppress round-off accumulation. Time-averaged quantities were collected over 10 impeller revolutions after an initial 5-revolution transient flush, confirmed sufficient by monitoring running averages of NIH to within 0.1% change per additional revolution. Solver conservation errors (mass imbalance) were below 1×10⁻⁸ kg/s for all cases. These results collectively satisfy the Gradation 4 requirement for demonstrated iterative and round-off error control with quantified residuals. The achieved level of 4 matches the required level, and no corrective actions are outstanding for this factor. Independent verification of convergence behaviour was performed by a reviewer not involved in the original simulation runs, confirming the residual histories and conservation checks reported in Appendix D. This factor is considered fully satisfied for the purposes of the MRL 5 credibility assessment and requires no further action prior to regulatory submission. All supporting data are archived with unique document identifiers in the project repository and are available for FDA inspection upon request."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Use error must be controlled at Gradation 3: documented simulation setup checklist, independent review of boundary condition inputs and mesh setup by a second analyst, and records showing no deviations from approved simulation protocols.",
      "rationale": "A 47-item simulation setup checklist was developed and completed for each of the five operating point simulations. An independent analyst reviewed all boundary condition input files, mesh quality reports, and turbulence model selections before execution. No deviations from the approved simulation protocol were recorded. Setup review records are stored in the project document management system with electronic signatures from both the primary analyst and the independent reviewer."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form uncertainty must be characterised at Gradation 4: multiple turbulence models and hemolysis constitutive models evaluated, with sensitivity of NIH predictions to model form choices quantified and shown to be within the validation uncertainty band.",
      "rationale": "Three turbulence models were evaluated (k-ω SST, realizable k-ε, and Spalart-Allmaras). NIH predictions varied by up to 18% across turbulence model choices at the highest shear operating point (8 L/min, 3500 RPM), exceeding the experimental uncertainty band of ±12%. Two hemolysis power-law models (Giersiepen-Wurzinger and Heuser-Opitz) were also compared, yielding NIH differences of up to 22%. The spread attributable to model form uncertainty is therefore larger than the validation uncertainty at one operating point, which prevents achievement of Gradation 4. The k-ω SST model with the Giersiepen-Wurzinger correlation was selected as the primary model based on best aggregate agreement, but the model form sensitivity is acknowledged as a residual uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs must be characterised at Gradation 4: all uncertain input parameters identified, probability distributions assigned based on experimental calibration data, and a formal UQ study (Monte Carlo or equivalent) propagating input uncertainty to QoI uncertainty with convergence demonstrated.",
      "rationale": "A Monte Carlo UQ study with 1000 Latin hypercube samples was conducted over five uncertain input parameters: inlet turbulence intensity (uniform ±15% of nominal), blood analogue dynamic viscosity (normal, CV=3%), hemolysis model exponent α (normal, mean 0.785, SD 0.05), hemolysis model coefficient C (log-normal, CV=12%), and rotational speed (normal, ±0.1 RPM). Convergence of the NIH mean and 95th percentile was confirmed by comparing 500-sample and 1000-sample estimates, showing less than 1% change. Output uncertainty intervals are reported as 90% confidence intervals on NIH at each operating point."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples must be characterised at Gradation 3: experimental specimens (pump units) documented with manufacturing tolerances, and unit-to-unit variability assessed through replicate testing on at least two pump units.",
      "rationale": "Two FDA generic pump units were fabricated to the published geometry specification. CMM measurements confirmed all critical dimensions were within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Replicate hemolysis experiments were conducted on both units at three overlapping operating points. Inter-unit NIH variability was below 6% (within the measurement uncertainty band), indicating that manufacturing variability does not introduce significant additional uncertainty into the validation dataset."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Equivalency of input parameters must be demonstrated at Gradation 3: a parameter mapping table showing that all simulation boundary conditions are derived from or traceable to experimental measurements, with differences between simulated and experimentally measured inlet/outlet conditions quantified.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table (Appendix B) maps each simulation boundary condition to its experimental source measurement, including instrument type, calibration date, and uncertainty. Inlet velocity profiles were derived from PIV measurements at the pump inlet plane rather than assuming uniform inflow. Outlet pressure was set to match the time-averaged pressure transducer reading. All mapped parameters are within the measurement uncertainty of their experimental counterparts, confirming Gradation 3 equivalency."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The 13-factor credibility assessment for COU2 (VAD hemolysis prediction, MRL 5) is accepted for regulatory submission. Seven factors achieved their required levels; six factors achieved one level below required, with documented corrective action items and residual uncertainty characterisation. The Monte Carlo UQ study provides quantified prediction intervals on NIH at all five operating points. The overall credibility evidence package is judged sufficient to support the regulatory decision, with acknowledged limitations in model form uncertainty and blood-analogue-to-blood extrapolation documented in the V&V report.",
